        Buddy said, "Excellent data — Section Three: Allergies and Sensitivities."

        At least this section was relevant.

        Kira listed what she knew — mild lactose intolerance, no others documented. Buddy provided medical file specifics. Remedy's robot took notes — mechanical fingers tapping against a salvaged data pad.

        Remedy said, "Good news — none of your allergens exist in plant chemistry here. Bad news — I have no idea if you'll react to novel fungal proteins. We'll need to test each compound."

        Kira asked carefully, "Test how?"

        Remedy said, "Small dose — wait twenty minutes — check for reaction. Standard allergy protocol."

        Twenty minutes. Per compound. While starving.

        Kira asked, "How many compounds are we testing?"

        Remedy said, "Eight to ten — covering proteins, carbohydrates, fats, and what vitamins I can synthesize."

        So... three hours minimum. Plus the hour already spent on forms. Her stomach was going to digest her spine at this rate.

        Kira asked, phrasing it strategically, "Can we start testing while finishing the assessment — to optimize the timeline?"

        Holloway said, "Excellent process improvement suggestion!"

        Holloway asked, "Remedy, can you begin compound synthesis?"

        Remedy said, "Already growing the first batch — protein compound alpha — should be ready in fifteen minutes."

        Finally. Progress.

        Holloway said, "Section Four: Texture Preferences — Section Five: Temperature Preferences — Section Six: Meal Frequency Requirements."

        Kira answered on autopilot while watching mushrooms grow.

        Remedy's chemistry was fascinating despite the hunger. Different mushroom varieties for different compounds — each specifically engineered for particular nutrients. Remedy's robot harvested them carefully, extracting compounds into small containers.

        Remedy announced, "First test ready — protein alpha — complete amino acid profile, derived from an oyster mushroom variant. Small sample for allergy screening."

        The robot offered a tiny amount of grayish paste on a salvaged spoon.

        Kira ate it.

        Bland. Slightly earthy. Texture like ground meat that had given up on life.

        But _food_.

        Remedy said, "Now we wait twenty minutes — watching for skin reactions, respiratory distress, gastrointestinal upset."

        ¶

        Twenty minutes felt like years.

        Holloway said, "Section Seven: Nutritional Education and Meal Planning Preferences."

        Holloway asked, "Would you like instructional materials about balanced nutrition?"

        Kira said, "No."

        Holloway asked, "Meal planning worksheets?"

        Kira said, "No."

        Holloway asked, "Access to dietary consultation services?"

        Kira said, "I just want food."

        Holloway said, "Noted: prefers independent meal management!"

        Scout had settled into an anxious vigil, watching her closely. The little plant could probably sense her mounting desperation.

        Twenty minutes passed.

        Remedy announced, "No allergic reaction detected — protein alpha approved. Next: carbohydrate compound."

        The process repeated: small sample — wait — watch. Each test took twenty to thirty minutes.

        Carbohydrate compound — mushroom-derived sugars and starches. Slightly sweet, weird texture.
